          "50":
              "Vegetables are food items characterized by their low-fat content, and if present in some varieties, the fats are easily absorbed since they come from fiber. Vegetables are a source of essential carbohydrates that provide the body with energy. They are rich in iron, which is available in legumes. The high water content in vegetables provides numerous benefits to the body, such as facilitating digestion and providing flexibility to body organs. The most important component in vegetables is cellulose, which is not absorbed by the body but remains in the intestines, stimulating their activity. It acts as a natural laxative for the digestive system and stimulates the glands to secrete digestive enzymes",
          "51": "Non-starchy vegetables",
          "52":
              "Non-starchy vegetables are a healthy food choice for people with diabetes. The list of non-starchy vegetables includes broccoli, carrots, artichokes, celery, cucumbers, and onions. Non-starchy vegetables are a good source of dietary fiber, which can generally help slow the absorption of sugar into the bloodstream. They also contain vitamins, minerals, and antioxidants that are beneficial for your overall health. Additionally, they are low in calories and carbohydrates.",
          "53": "Cucumbers",
          "54":
              "Cucumbers are a good vegetable for diabetics who suffer from high blood sugar levels, as they are low in calories and high in fiber content. ",
          "55":
              "Cucumbers may also help lower blood sugar levels because they contain a hormone needed by beta cells to produce insulin.",
          "56": "Tomatoes",
          "57":
              "Tomatoes are a food that does not cause a spike in blood sugar levels. They are also a good source of fiber and vitamins A and C, which are important for diabetics. Dietary fiber helps slow the absorption of sugar into the bloodstream, and vitamins A and C are antioxidants that help protect various cells in the body from damage. For these reasons, tomatoes are among the best foods for diabetics",
          "58": "Broccoli",
          "59":
              " Broccoli contains a compound called sulforaphane, which naturally lowers blood sugar levels. A scientific study concluded that broccoli, which contains sulforaphane",
          "60":
              "reduces markers of oxidative stress and blood sugar levels, and also enhances insulin sensitivity",
          "61": "Spinach",
          "62":
              "Spinach contains many vitamins, fiber, protein, carotene, and minerals that are nutritious for diabetics. The reason you might choose to eat spinach if you have high blood sugar levels is that its glycemic index is zero.",
          "63": "Asparagus",
          "64":
              "Asparagus contains a very low amount of carbohydrates, approximately 7 grams per cup, making it suitable for diabetics who want to lower their blood sugar levels",
          "65": "leafy green vegetables",
          "66":
              "There is a close relationship between consuming two to three servings of leafy green vegetables per week and a reduced likelihood of developing certain types of cancer, heart disease, and diabetes. These vegetables help maintain stable blood sugar levels, and consuming one cup of leafy green vegetables daily can lower the risk of developing diabetes by 14%.",
          "67":
              "Since you are a diabetic, you may wonder if fruit is off-limits for you. The answer is that you can eat certain types of fruit in moderation. Fruit, in general, is a great source of nutrients, fiber, and antioxidants. Here is a list of the top 10 fruits for diabetics: citrus fruits like oranges, apples, berries such as blueberries and cranberries, strawberries, avocados, peaches, plums, cherries, and pears",
          "68": "Berries",
          "69":
              "Berries are fruits rich in vitamins, fiber, and antioxidants, making them beneficial for diabetics as they help improve insulin sensitivity and reduce the amount of glucose in the body. Consuming two cups of berries, equivalent to 250 grams, contributes to lowering blood sugar levels",
          "70": "citrus fruits",
          "71":
              "Fruits like oranges, grapefruits, and other citrus fruits are rich in fiber and plant compounds such as polyphenols and naringenin, which are anti-diabetic. Citrus fruits reduce the risk of developing diabetes because they do not raise blood sugar levels as some other fruits do",
          "72": "Apples",
          "73":
              "Apples contain important plant compounds such as chlorogenic acid and quercetin, which help reduce blood sugar levels and protect the body from developing diabetes.",
          "74": "Consuming nuts may help control blood sugar levels in diabetics, and they are generally one of the best foods for diabetics. Nuts are a good source of protein, fiber, and healthy fats, and they also contain magnesium, a mineral that helps regulate blood sugar levels. Some of the most beneficial types of nuts for diabetics include walnuts, Brazil nuts, cashews, and hazelnuts Although nuts are high in fat and calories, eating them in moderation may help prevent weight gain and keep weight under control and maintain healthy levels",
          "75": "This is often due to the potential ability of nuts to suppress appetite and promote feelings of satiety for longer hours, which may reduce the desire to eat extra amounts of calorie-rich food But it should be noted that nuts should be eaten in moderation, as excessive intake may cause weight gain",
          "76": "Use nuts as a healthy alternative to some high-calorie meals, instead of adding them to the diet as side meals Eat only a moderate serving of nuts a day, and the allowable serving is roughly equivalent to a small handful of nuts in a fist",
          "77": "pistachios ",
          "78": "One study showed that consuming pistachios by individuals with type 2 diabetes may help improve their overall health. This is often attributed to the high magnesium content and a variety of antioxidants found in this type of nut, which may help with the following: Slowing the rate of increase in blood sugar levels after meals Reducing inflammation Suppressing appetite",
          "79": "Walnuts ",
          "80": "Walnuts may have numerous potential benefits for diabetics and individuals looking to reduce their risk of developing diabetes, as studies suggest: One study found that consuming walnuts may help enhance feelings of fullness and promote weight loss, which could contribute to obesity prevention Another study indicated that regular walnut consumption among women may help lower their risk of developing type 2 diabetes The potential benefits of walnuts in this regard are often attributed to their high content of alpha-lipoic acid, an important fatty acid that may help reduce inflammation As a result, this can lower the risk of many chronic diseases that inflammation can exacerbate, such as Alzheimer’s disease, diabetes, and heart disease",
          "81": "Almonds",
          "82": "Giving this type of nut to diabetics may help improve their overall health. One study showed that consuming a small amount of almonds daily for 12 consecutive weeks may help regulate blood sugar levels and reduce the risk of heart disease in individuals with type 2 diabetes",
          "83": "Fish, especially fatty fish (such as salmon, tuna, and sardines), are among the best healthy foods for diabetics for the following reasons: These fish are rich in omega-3 fatty acids, which have been shown to lower blood sugar levels and improve insulin sensitivity Fish are also a good source of protein and low in calories Additionally, they are an excellent source of various vitamins and minerals, including vitamin D, selenium, and magnesium.",
          "84": "The protein found in fish and meat can help you control blood sugar levels and lose weight. Protein also aids in building and repairing tissues in your body. Additionally, protein is an important nutrient for diabetics, as it can help prevent or slow the progression of diabetes complications, such as kidney disease Fish are also beneficial for heart health. Consume heart-healthy fish at least twice a week. Fish such as salmon, mackerel, tuna, and sardines are rich in omega-3 fatty acids, which can protect against heart disease. Avoid eating fried fish and fish that have high levels of mercury, such as cod fish",
          "85": "Low-fat or fat-free dairy products are among the best foods for diabetics, and the American Diabetes Association (ADA) recommends that diabetics consume fat-free or low-fat dairy products. Dairy products are an excellent source of calcium, potassium, and magnesium, and they also contain vitamin A and some B vitamins. Some of the notable low-fat or fat-free dairy products allowed for diabetics include unsweetened almond milk, unsweetened soy milk, low-fat cheese, light cream, fat-free milk and yogurt, and low-fat natural cheeses.",
          "86": "Sources of cholesterol include fatty dairy products, fatty animal proteins, and egg yolks. Do not consume more than 200 mg of cholesterol per day.",
          "87": "Good fats, also known as healthy fats, are essential for a variety of reasons. They help you absorb vitamins, build cell membranes, and produce hormones. Healthy fats also help maintain stable blood sugar levels, which is important if you have diabetes, as unstable blood sugar levels are known to lead to serious health complications Some good sources of healthy fats include canola oil, avocado oil, olive oil, and coconut oil.",
          "88": "Olive oil ",
          "89": "Olive oil plays an important role for diabetics, as it was mentioned in a study that the consumption of olive oil for type II diabetics helps in: Reduce high blood sugar level. Improvement of blood insulin levelling. Enhance glucose tolerance. Improve insulin sensitivity in the blood. Reduce cellular death of cells responsible for insulin production Increase the number of cells responsible for the manufacture of insulin.",
          "90": "Coconut oil ",
          "91": "Coconut oil stimulates insulin production and reduces insulin resistance levels in the body. It helps maintain stable blood sugar levels and encourages the body to utilize blood glucose more effectively. Therefore, coconut oil may help prevent diabetes or improve a diabetic patient's ability to keep their condition under control, especially for those with type 2 diabetes.",
          "92": "Whole grains are an important part of a healthy diet for diabetics, as they are rich in fiber and various nutrients and can help control blood sugar levels. Whole grains include whole wheat, brown rice, oats, barley, quinoa, wild rice, buckwheat, bulgur (cracked wheat), and millet. It's worth noting that consuming foods high in dietary fiber is one of the ways to maintain digestive health. It is important to note that carbohydrates, such as starch found in grains, have the greatest impact on blood sugar levels because all carbohydrates are ultimately broken down into simple sugars by the body. The body takes longer to digest complex carbohydrates and convert them into simple sugars, making them a better option for everyone, including diabetics. Experts recommend that individuals with blood sugar level issues limit their carbohydrate intake to maintain healthy blood sugar levels; however, it is not advisable to eliminate grains entirely from the daily diet due to the benefits of consuming carbohydrates in a balanced diet. Here are the key benefits of whole grains for diabetics: - Reducing the risk of developing type 2 diabetes. - Controlling blood sugar levels.  - Lowering the chances of developing diabetes.",
          "93": "Whole wheat grains",
          "94": "Consuming whole wheat grains helps regulate blood sugar levels and keep them within normal and healthy ranges due to their relatively low glycemic index. Whole grains are high in dietary fiber, and fiber is a type of carbohydrate that can improve blood sugar levels for the following reasons:  - The difficulty the body has in digesting fiber can slow down digestion and the absorption of nutrients from food, thus preventing sudden spikes in blood sugar and maintaining sugar levels within a healthy range.  The potential of fiber to improve insulin sensitivity in the body.  Whole wheat grains are also a good source of various minerals and vitamins, such as B vitamins, vitamin E, zinc, and magnesium.",
          "95": "Oats and Brown rice",
          "96": "Oats help lower blood sugar levels by increasing insulin sensitivity, which is one of the main benefits of oats for kidney patients. Brown rice is one of the beneficial whole grains for diabetics as it:- Promotes heart health. - Helps manage diabetes. - May play a role in weight loss. - Improves overall body health. - Is a gluten-free source.   ",
          "97": "However, if you want to try following a gluten-free diet, there is no reason to give up grains. Experts recommend that most people with blood sugar problems consume whole grains, as they are nutritious and high in dietary fiber, which helps maintain healthy blood sugar levels. Coriander seeds help maintain stable blood sugar levels in diabetics by controlling the secretion of insulin in the body. Different seeds have various effects on blood sugar levels. Some, like chia seeds and flax seeds, can help control blood sugar levels, while others, like pumpkin seeds and sunflower seeds, can cause an increase in blood sugar. Therefore, if you have diabetes, it is important to monitor your seed intake and choose seeds that do not raise blood sugar levels.  Flax seeds can enhance the effects of blood sugar-lowering medications taken by diabetics, which can be very harmful. Therefore, you should avoid consuming flax seeds.   ",
          "98": "Some people ask whether legumes raise blood sugar. It is important to know that legumes such as beans, peas, and lentils have a low glycemic index (GI), which means they have a slow impact on blood sugar levels.  Among the most beneficial legumes for diabetics are chickpeas, black-eyed peas, and beans.  Legumes can sometimes cause an increase in blood sugar levels because they contain a significant amount of carbohydrates. Therefore, diabetics should pay attention to their diet, especially when including legumes.  It is recommended to combine legumes with non-starchy vegetables, low-sugar fruits, and protein-rich foods to create an ideal meal without affecting blood sugar levels.",
          "99": "Red beans and Chickpeas",
          "100": "Red beans are beneficial for diabetics, as their rich nutritional content, especially fiber, helps regulate blood sugar levels, keeping them under control and preventing sudden spikes. Chickpeas are also very beneficial for diabetics. Their low glycemic index makes them suitable for maintaining blood sugar levels even in diabetics. Chickpeas contain a high amount of fiber and slow-digesting sugars, as well as a high content of proteins, calcium, potassium, and folic acid.",
          "101": "Meals with saturated fats",
          "102": "Diabetes increases the risk of blocked and hardened arteries, making you more susceptible to heart disease and stroke. Foods containing the following elements can hinder your efforts to maintain a heart-healthy diet: Saturated fats: Avoid fatty dairy products and fatty animal proteins, such as butter, beef, sausages, and bacon. Also, limit your intake of coconut and palm kernel oils. Trans fats: Avoid trans fats found in ready-made snack foods, baked goods, shortening, and solid margarine. Cholesterol: Sources of cholesterol include fatty dairy products, fatty animal proteins, egg yolks, liver, and other organ meats. Do not consume more than 200 mg of cholesterol per day. Sodium: Do not consume more than 2,300 mg of sodium per day. Your doctor may suggest a lower amount if you have high blood pressure.",
          "103": "Sports system instructions",
          "104": "Engaging in regular physical activity has numerous positive effects and benefits on human health, especially for those with diabetes, as it is a key factor in regulating blood sugar levels. The type of exercise varies depending on age, gender, health condition, and individual ability, and your doctor will monitor your physical condition to determine the appropriate exercises for you.",
          "105": "Benefits of physical activity for individuals with diabetes:",
          "106": "•	Lowering and regulating blood sugar and fat levels.  •	Reducing the body's resistance to insulin.   •	Increasing the number of insulin receptors, thereby optimizing the use of insulin in the body.  •	Reducing the amount of medication the patient needs.  •	Strengthening and building the body and muscles.  •	Helping with weight loss and maintaining an ideal weight.  •	Improving mental well-being.",
          "107": "The impact of physical activity on blood sugar depends on:",
          "108": "•	Blood glucose level before starting physical activity.   •	Intensity and duration of the activity.  •	Any changes in insulin doses.",
          "109": "Guidelines for starting physical activity:",
          "110": "•	Start gradually, then increase the duration and intensity of the activity to reach the desired and appropriate level for each individual. •	Prepare the body for physical activity by starting with warm-up exercises for 5 to 10 minutes, and end the session with relaxation exercises for 5 to 10 minutes. •	Allocate rest periods ranging from 30 to 90 seconds when needed. •	Avoid physical activity in case of illness or sports-related injuries. •	Consult your doctor before engaging in any activity or following the regimen recommended by your physician.",
          "111": "Precautions when engaging in physical activity:",
          "112": "Carry an identification card indicating that the person has diabetes.  Drink enough fluids before, during, and after exercise to prevent dehydration, which can affect blood sugar levels. Carry a small juice box, sugar cubes, or candy to use in case of low blood sugar.  Also, carry a backup snack if the physical activity will last more than half an hour.   Avoid injecting insulin into areas of the body that will be used during exercise, as using the injected area can speed up insulin absorption, potentially leading to a hypoglycemic episode. For example, avoid injecting insulin into the thigh if walking is planned.  The doctor may allow a reduction in the insulin dose before exercise if necessary.  Avoid physical activity during times when insulin action is at its peak.  When using an insulin pump, temporary basal rate programming can be used.  Blood sugar levels should be checked before, during, and after physical activity, and monitored every half hour if the activity lasts longer to ensure quick intervention in case of low blood sugar.  Wear appropriate athletic shoes and take care of your feet.",
          "113": "Based on your age, weight, and level of diabetes, your doctor will provide you with suitable exercise tasks to engage in.",
